						<div class="postbody">Wow thanks for the quick reply!
<br />
<br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha"><li>Rip open one of the dwindling supply of VRC6 games for each copy that you plan to make.</li></ol></div><br /><br />Although I only wanted to make one VRC6 cart, you're right, and I don't want to have to destroy a good game just for that chip. Option B sounds really complicated. Is it legal? It would be pretty awesome if I could make a new VRC6 chip.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If you can't read Japanese, stick with normal carts. Those are easy to make; kits for NROM (#000), CNROM (#003), UNROM (#002), BNROM (#034), AOROM (#007), and S*ROM (#001) are available from retrousb.com.</div>
<br />
<br />I guess I'll learn Japanese! This would be so much easier because most of the information I want to read is Japanese. I know its impractical but I really like the Famicom carts, and I'm willing to put a lot of time and effort into making a flasher and homebrew carts similar to the ones RetroUSB offers for the NES. I think it would be interesting and fun to learn about programming and electronics, I'm not looking for a fast an cheap method. But I don't know where to start. I read a little about molding plastic, because I want to make my own cases. But I other than that I don't know what to do.
<br />
<br />EDIT: Sorry for rambling on.
<br /><strong>TL;DR:</strong> How do I go about making a normal (no VRC6) Famicom cart and cart flahser? If you don't know can you point me in the right direction so I can figure it out myself please?
<br />
<br />Thanks in advance!</div>

