				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I apologize if I sounded rude. It's just that a lot of people get grand ideas about making things using parts from uncommon to rare Famicom games. Every time you put new ROMs into a VRC6 game, that's one fewer copy of that game. And if you make a game in a Latin-alphabet language (e.g. English, German, Spanish, French, Italian, Esperanto), and you distribute cartridges to the public, most players will have a 72-pin NES that has <em>not</em> been modified for expansion sound passthrough.
<br />
<br />In the following paragraph, try plugging the bold words into Google:
<br />
<br />Once you have your game, you'll want to open the game's case, desolder the PRG ROM, and solder in a <strong>DIP socket</strong>. Then you'll want to store your program on a <strong>flash memory</strong> chip (<strong>29F040</strong> series is common) using an <strong>EPROM programmer</strong> such as one made by <strong>Wellon</strong> or <strong>Willem</strong>. Then pop the ROM into the socket and hope it works. Most boards made by Nintendo need a few wires to be rerouted due to cost- and space-saving shortcuts that Nintendo took, but <strong>ReproPak</strong> boards from retrousb.com won't need rewiring.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

